The {{nihongo|'''Kinyakurumazuka Kofun'''|禁野車塚古墳|}} is a [[Kofun period]] [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|keyhole-shaped Kofun]], located in the Miyanosaka neighborhood of the city of [[:en:Hirakata, Osaka|Hirakata, Osaka]] in the [[:en:Kansai region|Kansai region]] of [[:en:Japan|Japan]]. The tumulus was designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1972 with the area under protection expanded in 2007.<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/172555 |title=禁野車塚古墳 |trans-title=Kinyakurumazuka Kofun|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 20, 2020}}</ref>
==Overview== The Kinyakurumazuka Kofun is a {{nihongo|''zenpō-kōen-fun''|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|2=ja|3=前方後円墳|4=ko|5=전방후원분|6=zh|7=前方後圓墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|comement=second one attempting to fix this error|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}}, which is shaped like a keyhole, having one square end and one circular end, when viewed from above. It is located in a residential area between the rivers of the Hirakata hills extending to the northwestern foot of the [[:en:Mount Ikoma|Ikoma Mountains]] on the bank of the Amano River near its confluence with the [[:en:Yodo River|Yodo River]]. It is one of the few ancient Kofuns that remain on the south bank of the Yodo River basin, and since the Yodo River was one of the main transportation routes from [[Seto Inland Sea]] to the center of the [[:en:Kinai region|Kinai region]], it is regarded to be of great significance to understanding the Kofun period history of the area. The tumulus has a length of 120 meters and is orientated to the west. The anterior portion is low and has a "drumstick" shape, whereas the posterior circular portion is high. There is no moat, but ''[[fukiishi]]'' have been found on the lower south side of the posterior circular portion and both cylindrical ''[[:en:Haniwa|Haniwa]]'' and figurative ''haniwa'' have been found. The tumulus has been extensively surveyed, but no [[archaeological excavation]] has yet been conducted, so details of its [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]] are uncertain. It is presumed to be a vertical pit-type stone chamber based on piece of stone slab at the top of the posterior circle. Based on the shape and construction technique and style of ''haniwa'', the tumulus is believed to date from the early Kofun period, or around the 4th century.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The tumulus is located about a five-minute walk from [[:en:Miyanosaka Station (Osaka)|Miyanosaka Station]] on the [[:en:Keihan Katano Line|Keihan Katano Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
;Total length: 120 meters: ;Anterior rectangular portion: 55 meters wide, 2-tier ;Posterior circular portion: 63 meter diameter, 2-tiers
